    <item>
      <title>Budget Reconciliation Progresses, Maybe</title>
      <author>Daniel Schuman       </author>
      <link>https://www.govtrack.us/posts/491/2025-03-31_budget-reconciliation-progresses-maybe</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.govtrack.us/posts/491/2025-03-31_budget-reconciliation-progresses-maybe</guid>
      <pubDate>Tue, 01 Apr 2025 00:21:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>                &lt;p&gt;Hello Govtrackers, Congress will be very busy this week.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The Senate may vote on terminating a presidential declaration of national emergency, according to the newspaper &lt;a href="https://rollcall.com/2025/03/31/this-week-senate-to-vote-on-tariff-emergency-ahead-of-possible-budget-vote-a-rama/?ref=com.devaary.cqrc.rollcall.v01"&gt;&lt;em&gt;Roll Call&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;. According to a &lt;a href="https://www.kaine.senate.gov/press-releases/kaine-klobuchar-and-warner-announce-expected-vote-timing-on-their-bill-to-undo-canada-tariffs-that-will-raise-costs"&gt;press release&lt;/a&gt; from Sens. Kaine, Klobuchar, and Warner, the Senate is expected to vote Tuesday on &lt;a href="https://www.kaine.senate.gov/imo/media/doc/ros25392.pdf"&gt;this privileged resolution&lt;/a&gt; to “undo President Trump’s tariffs on Canadian goods.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The Senate may also vote on a “compromise budget resolution,” &lt;a href="https://rollcall.com/2025/03/31/this-week-senate-to-vote-on-tariff-emergency-ahead-of-possible-budget-vote-a-rama/?ref=com.devaary.cqrc.rollcall.v01"&gt;according to &lt;em&gt;Roll Call&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;, which could &lt;a href="https://www.politico.com/news/2025/03/30/senate-gop-to-start-moving-budget-plan-as-soon-as-wednesday-00259960?nname=inside-congress&amp;amp;nid=0000014f-1646-d88f-a1cf-5f46b4be0000&amp;amp;nrid=1a3f1abb-3676-4ca7-80a0-d93a12bb5910"&gt;happen as soon as Wednesday&lt;/a&gt;, according to &lt;em&gt;Politico&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Step one in the budget reconciliation process, the measure would provide directions to committees to draft legislation to change federal spending and taxation levels within certain guidelines. The guidelines are what are being negotiated.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The legislation the committees would approve would be combined into one big bill that would then be considered by both chambers of Congress. Crucially, such legislation would only need the support of 51 senators to pass, which means that it could pass with Republican support only.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The budget resolution to be voted on this week would take the form of an amendment to the previously-passed House resolution. We do not yet know what it would contain, but presumably it would include some senate priorities. The Senate had previously &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/sconres7"&gt;passed its own budget resolution&lt;/a&gt;, but that is being set aside. The big political issue is whether Congress enacts one budget resolution containing much of Pres. Trump’s wish list, which is harder to do because it may contain provisions that some Republicans could not easily support, or to break it into two bills and pass the less controversial part first. Another issue is whether the legislation addresses raising or suspending the debt ceiling. On that point, the Congressional Budget Office said &lt;a href="https://www.cbo.gov/publication/60887"&gt;the government’s ability to borrow money&lt;/a&gt; will be exhausted by August or September.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The House of Representatives largely will be waiting to see what happens in the Senate. The clock is ticking, as both chambers are in for the next two weeks, and then out for two weeks for the April recess.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;On the &lt;a href="https://www.majorityleader.gov/schedule/weekly-schedule.htm"&gt;House floor this week&lt;/a&gt; are four bills that will be considered pursuant to a rule, which means they only need a majority to pass that chamber. Among those bills are one that would &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hr1526/text/rh"&gt;limit the ability of federal judges&lt;/a&gt; to stop the federal government from engaging in actions that may be unlawful and cause irreparable harm to people; another that would &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hr22"&gt;make it harder for everyday Americans to register to vote&lt;/a&gt; by requiring a higher standard of proof that they are citizens; as well as &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/s153"&gt;a resolution&lt;/a&gt; to disapprove of regulations that &lt;a href="https://www.consumerfinance.gov/rules-policy/final-rules/overdraft-lending-very-large-financial-institutions-final-rule/"&gt;protect consumers against overly large overdraft fees&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/sjres28"&gt;a resolution&lt;/a&gt; to disapprove of regulations that allowed the Consumer Financial Protection Bureau &lt;a href="https://files.consumerfinance.gov/f/documents/cfpb_final-rule_general-use-digital-consumer-payment-applications_2024-11.pdf"&gt;to regulate some risks to consumers&lt;/a&gt;. Seven bills are on suspension, which means they require a 2/3s vote to pass the House. Most of them relate to taxes.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;There are &lt;a href="https://www.congress.gov/committee-schedule/weekly/2025/03/31"&gt;forty-eight committee meetings&lt;/a&gt; this week in the House and Senate. Some of them line up with the bills to be considered on the House and Senate floor, such as a House Judiciary Committee hearing on “judicial overreach” and a Senate Judiciary Committee hearing on the universal jurisdiction of judges. There are a handful of appropriations hearings, which address the levels at which the government should be funded, and there are a bunch of senate hearings on Trump’s nominees for various offices. We also see what appears to be the start of hearings relating to the National Defense Authorization Act, a major bill passed every year that controls the activities of the armed forces. The hearing that I am most excited about concerns funding for officers in the House of Representatives, which is probably less consequential than others but is related significantly to the operations of our Congress. I’ll be there in person.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Have a good week.&lt;/p&gt;      </description>
      <category>Legislative Preview</category>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Legislation, Confirmations, Opposing Regulations</title>
      <author>Amy West       </author>
      <link>https://www.govtrack.us/posts/490/2025-03-28_legislation-confirmations-opposing-regulations</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.govtrack.us/posts/490/2025-03-28_legislation-confirmations-opposing-regulations</guid>
      <pubDate>Fri, 28 Mar 2025 13:51:59 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>                &lt;p&gt;This week the House passed a few bills, the Senate continued confirming Executive Branch nominees and both chambers voted against a variety of regulations established by the Biden Administration.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The House has &lt;em&gt;not&lt;/em&gt; yet voted on &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/s1077"&gt;S. 1077: District of Columbia Local Funds Act, 2025&lt;/a&gt; which would restore Washington, D.C.'s funding levels even though the Senate voted for it unanimously and &lt;a href="https://www.semafor.com/article/03/25/2025/dc-budget-fix-faces-slowing-momentum-in-congress"&gt;the White House has said it supports this bill&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The House will also continue to include &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/members/elise_stefanik/412648"&gt;Rep. Stefanik (R-NY21)&lt;/a&gt;. She had been the nominee for the US Ambassador to the United Nations, but the Trump Administration has become worried about its extremely narrow margin in the House and &lt;a href="https://www.axios.com/2025/03/28/elise-stefanik-mike-johnson-trump-un-ambassador"&gt;withdrew her nomination&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h2&gt;Bills&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hr359"&gt;H.R. 359: Cost-Share Accountability Act of 2025&lt;/a&gt;, which would amend the Energy Policy Act of 2005 to require reporting relating to certain cost-share requirements, passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/h72"&gt;405-0&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hr1326"&gt;H.R. 1326: DOE and USDA Interagency Research Act&lt;/a&gt;, which would provide for Department of Energy and Department of Agriculture joint research and development activities such as grid modernization and security, rural technology development, and wildfire risks and prevention, passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/h73"&gt;372-35&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hr1534"&gt;H.R. 1534: IMPACT Act&lt;/a&gt;, which would provide for research and development of advanced technologies to improve the efficiency of cement, concrete, and asphalt production, passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/h74"&gt;350-73&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hr1048"&gt;H.R. 1048: DETERRENT Act&lt;/a&gt;, which would limit presumed foreign influence on US campuses by lowering reporting thresholds for gifts and requiring reporting of individual grants and contracts, passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/h83"&gt;241-169&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;/ul&gt; &lt;h2&gt;Confirmations&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;Among many confirmations of sub-cabinet level positions this week, these two are notable because of the importance of the FDA and NIH to the daily health of US residents. The Washington Post &lt;a href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/health/2025/03/25/bhattacharya-nih-director-cdc-makary/"&gt;wrote about both nominees&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt;Makary, Commissioner of Food and Drug Administration confirmed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/s143"&gt;56-44&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;Bhattacharya, Director of the National Institutes of Health confirmed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/s141"&gt;53-47&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;/ul&gt; &lt;h2&gt;Opposing Regulations&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;The official information is all below, but to summarize, one or both chambers voted to let financial services companies continue to not report crypto sales, to keep appliances less efficient and to allow banks to charge customers as much as they want in fees.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hjres25"&gt;H. J. Res. 25:&lt;/a&gt; Providing for congressional disapproval under chapter 8 of title 5, United States Code, of the rule submitted by the Internal Revenue Service relating to "Gross Proceeds Reporting by Brokers That Regularly Provide Services Effectuating Digital Asset Sales" passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/s151"&gt;70-28&lt;/a&gt; and goes to the President for signing next.&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hjres24"&gt;H.J.Res. 24:&lt;/a&gt; Providing for congressional disapproval under chapter 8 of title 5, United States Code, of the rule submitted by the Department of Energy relating to “Energy Conservation Program: Energy Conservation Standards for Walk-In Coolers and Walk-In Freezers” passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/h77"&gt;203-182&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hjres75"&gt;H.J.Res. 75:&lt;/a&gt; Providing for congressional disapproval under chapter 8 of title 5, United States Code, of the rule submitted by the Office of Energy Efficiency and Renewable Energy, Department of Energy relating to "Energy Conservation Program: Energy Conservation Standards for Commercial Refrigerators, Freezers, and Refrigerator-Freezers" passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/h78"&gt;214-193&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/sjres18"&gt;S.J.Res. 18:&lt;/a&gt; A joint resolution disapproving the rule submitted by the Bureau of Consumer Financial Protection relating to “Overdraft Lending: Very Large Financial Institutions” passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/119-2025/s153"&gt;52-48&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;/ul&gt;      </description>
      <category>Legislative Recap</category>
